What is the relationship between TypeScriprt and JavaScript?
TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript — every valid JavaScript file is also valid TypeScript. Microsoft created it in 2012 to add static typing to JavaScript.

Key relationships:

TypeScript adds to JavaScript:

Static type annotations (const x: number = 5)
Interfaces and type aliases
Enums
Generics
Access modifiers (public, private, protected)
Compile-time error checking
TypeScript compiles to JavaScript:

The TypeScript compiler (tsc) strips all type information and outputs plain .js files
Browsers and Node.js never see TypeScript — they only run the compiled JavaScript
You choose which JavaScript version to target (ES5, ES2020, etc.)
In practice:


// TypeScript source (.ts)
function greet(name: string): string {
  return `Hello, ${name}`;
}

// Compiled JavaScript output (.js)
function greet(name) {
  return `Hello, ${name}`;
}
Why use it?

Catches bugs at compile time rather than at runtime
Better IDE autocomplete and refactoring support
Makes large codebases easier to maintain (which is why this project uses it)
The types only exist during development — at runtime it's just JavaScript.

